  "prompt": "Why isn't the Moon spinning?",
  "response": "The Moon is indeed spinning, but it does so in a way that is synchronized with its orbit around the Earth. This phenomenon is known as synchronous rotation or tidal locking. \n\nThe Moon takes about 27.3 days to complete one rotation on its axis and the same amount of time to orbit the Earth. As a result, the same side of the Moon always faces Earth. This is due to the gravitational interactions between the Earth and the Moon over millions of years, which caused the Moon's rotation period to slow down until it matched its orbital period.\n\nSo while it may seem like the Moon is \"not spinning\" because we only see one side of it, it is, in fact, rotating continuously.",
